[5] Guadeloupe
Date: Fri 15 Jan 2010
Source: Institut de Veille Sanitaire: Le point epidemiologique - N2 [in
French, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.invs.sante.fr/surveillance/dengue/points_guadeloupe/2010/pep_guadeloupe_2010_2_dengue.pdf>


Surveillance of cases clinically suggestive of dengue
-----------------------------------------------------
After being maintained over the last 2 weeks of Dec 2009 (weeks 2009-52 and
2009-53) at levels close to the maximum expected, there is a rapid rise and
a large number of cases clinically suggestive [of dengue virus infections]
during the 1st week of Jan (week 2010-01). With about 260 cases clinically
suggestive [of dengue] seen in consultation with general physicians during
the last week, the level reached was equivalent to that observed during the
2nd week of Dec [2009] and far surpasses the maximum level expected for the
period. The number of cases clinically suggestive of dengue fever is an
estimate for the entire population of Guadeloupe [based on] the number of
people who consulted a general practitioner for a clinical syndrome
suggestive of dengue. This estimation is performed using data collected
from the network of sentinel physicians.

Monitoring of laboratory confirmed cases
----------------------------------------
The evolution of the number of laboratory confirmed cases follows a dynamic
similar to that of the suggestive cases. After declining in the 3rd and 4th
weeks of Dec 2009 (week 2009-51 and 2009-52), we observed a significant
increase of almost 60 per cent in the number of laboratory confirmed cases
in week 53 [last week of Dec 2009]. Since early Dec [2009], the positivity
rate remained at a high level, each week ranging between 37 and 51 per cent
in the 5 weeks of Dec 2009.

Geographical distribution
-------------------------
The [number of] households identified [with dengue cases] in October [2009]
has increased and gradually generalized. The phenomenon [dengue outbreak]
was widespread on Grande Terre island. On Basse-Terre island, it was
widespread on the north east and north of the Windward Coast, including
Bay-Mahault, Petit Bourg, and Guava.

Surveillance of hospitalized cases
----------------------------------
After remaining stable between August and November 2009, the number of
laboratory confirmed cases hospitalized increased sharply in Dec 2009, with
a total of 20 cases. Since early January [2010], 5 laboratory confirmed
cases have been hospitalized. Since early December [2009] the 25 registered
cases have comprised 12 adults and 13 children. They are divided into 7
[cases] of classical dengue, 3 severe cases, one DHF, 4 incomplete
hemorrhagic types; the other 10 cases recently reported are being currently
classified.

Monitoring of [dengue virus, DENV] serotypes
--------------------------------------------
The DENV-2 serotype that was predominant to the end of the epidemic of 2007
has gradually given way to the DENV-1 serotype, which has circulated almost
exclusively since early 2009.

Situation analysis
------------------
After a period of stability observed during the period at the end of year
[2009], the monitoring indicators show a strong increase of virus
circulation. The phenomenon is widespread at this time save for some
southern windward coastal municipalities and southern and northern
Basse-Terre. The epidemiological situation, which corresponds to Phase 3 of
PSAG (program monitoring, warning and management of epidemics) for
Guadeloupe, is "epidemic risk," which will be reviewed by the Committee of
Experts on Infectious and Emerging Diseases that meets on 14 Jan [2010].

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>

[Unlike most of the dengue outbreak reports that come to ProMED-mail, this
one, and the French Antilles reports below, provide valuable information
about the dengue virus serotypes that are circulating there.

