[8] Brazil (Mato Grosso)
Date: Wed 13 Jan 2010
Source: O Documento [in Portuguese, trans & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.odocumento.com.br/materia.php?id=319927>


The state Secretariat of Health has announced partial data of dengue cases
for the 1st week of January 2010. Up to today's date (13 Jan [2010]), the
State of Mato Grosso has reported 1346 cases of the disease, 26 of them
reported as serious dengue cases. To date, the total number of reports of
deaths due to dengue are 4 cases, which are under investigation [apparently
not yet confirmed - Mod.TY]. The numbers are from the Coordination [office]
of Epidemiological Monitoring of SES/MT [state Secretariat of Health, Mato
Grosso].

The capital of Mato Grosso, Cuiaba has so far reported 234 cases of dengue.
Of these, 4 were reported as severe cases of the disease with no recorded
deaths from dengue.

In Varzea Grande to date, 122 cases of dengue have been reported. Of that
number, 5 were reported as severe cases of disease, with 2 deaths under
investigation.

Deaths in other municipalities that had reported dengue so far were: Pocone
(one case under investigation) and Rondonopolis (one case under investigation).

The state of Mato Grosso up until now has had an increase of 18.7 per cent
in reported dengue [cases] compared with the same period last year [2009].
The data relating to the partial close of the year 2009 are 58 410 cases of
dengue, of which 1405 cases were reported as severe disease. The
municipalities have until 15 Jan 2010 to pass along the data on dengue as
of the close of the year of 2009. Total dengue deaths in 2009 are 57 cases.
Of these deaths, 52 were confirmed, and 5 cases are under investigation.

This week, the government of Mato Grosso renewed the partnership of the
state with the municipalities of Cuiaba and Varzea Grande to fight dengue
with the hiring of mobile patrols carrying out the task of trash removal
from homes and vacant lots in the 2 cities for more than 30 days. This
period will also see the delivery of new machines for road consortia.

Through the Center for Strategic Information in Health Surveillance
(CLEVS), a reorganization was established with municipalities at risk of
and [having] epidemic disease, which included measures and strategic
actions in fighting and dealing with the disease through conferences about
the dengue situation.

--
